column23: $C  Also in 2019, Citigroup settled charges with the OCC for $30 million that it held foreclosed homes off the market for an impermissible period of longer than five years.
column24: $C  2019: Citigroup was one of five banks charged by the European Union with rigging foreign exchange trading. It paid the heaviest fine of ‚Ç¨310.8 million.
column25: $C  Also in 2018, Citigroup paid a fine of $10.5 million to the SEC for making ‚Äúfraudulently induced loans‚Äù in Mexico and in a separate action, for its traders engaging in unauthorized trading and hiding $81 million in losses.
column26: $C  2018: Citigroup agreed to pay $100 million to the New York State Attorney General‚Äôs office and 41 other states for its role in rigging the interest rate benchmark known as Libor.
column27: $C  Also in 2017, the CFPB fined Citigroup‚Äôs mortgage unit $28.8 million for declining to tell home borrowers about options to avoid foreclosure and throwing up roadblocks for homeowners to apply for relief.
column28: $C  2017: Consumer Financial Protection Bureau (CFPB) settles with Citigroup‚Äôs Citibank over a litany of abuses against student loan borrowers. The CFPB ordered Citi to pay $3.75 million in restitution and to pay a $2.75 million fine.
column29: $C  July 12, 2016: The Securities and Exchange Commission fined Citigroup Global Markets Inc. $7 million for failure to provide accurate trading records over a period of 15 years.
column30: $C  May 25, 2016: Citigroup agrees to pay $425 million to resolve claims brought by the Commodity Futures Trading Commission that it had rigged interest-rate benchmarks, including ISDAfix, from 2007 to 2012.
column31: $C  2015: Citicorp, unit of Citigroup, becomes admitted felon by pleading guilty to a felony charge in the matter of rigging foreign currency trading, paying a fine of $925 million to the Justice Department and $342 million to the Federal Reserve for a total of $1.267 billion.
column32: $C  November 2014: Citigroup pays more than $1 billion to settle civil allegations with regulators that it manipulated foreign currency markets. Other global banks settled at the same time.
column33: $C  July 14, 2014: The U.S. Department of Justice announces a $7 billion settlement with Citigroup for selling toxic mortgages to investors.
column34: $C  December 4, 2013: Citigroup admits to participating in the Yen Libor financial derivatives cartel to the European Commission and accepts a fine of $95 million.
column35: $C  September 25, 2013: Citigroup agrees to pay Freddie Mac $395 million to settle claims it sold it toxic mortgages.
column36: $C  July 1, 2013: Citigroup agrees to pay Fannie Mae $968 million for selling it toxic mortgage loans.
column37: $C  August 29, 2012: Citigroup agrees to settle a class action lawsuit for $590 million over claims it withheld from shareholders‚Äô knowledge that it had far greater exposure to subprime debt than it was reporting.
column38: $C  February 9, 2012: Citigroup agrees to pay $2.2 billion as its portion of the nationwide settlement of bank foreclosure fraud.
column39: $C  2011: SEC settles with Citigroup for $285 million over claims it misled investors in a $1 billion financial product.  Citigroup had selected approximately half the assets and was betting they would decline in value.
column40: $C  2010: SEC settles with Citigroup for $75 million over its misleading statements to investors that it had reduced its exposure to subprime mortgages to $13 billion when in fact the exposure was over $50 billion.
column41: $C  2008: The SEC forces Citigroup and UBS to buy back $30 billion in auction rate securities that were improperly sold to investors through misleading information.
column42: $C  2004: Citigroup paid $2.65 billion to WorldCom stock and bond holders over its role in the demise of the company. In the same year, Citigroup‚Äôs private bank was kicked out of Japan for money laundering.
column43: $C  2003: Citigroup pays $400 million to settle charges with U.S. regulators over issuing fraudulent research reports to the public on stocks it was pushing.
column44: $C 2001: Citigroup settled for $215 million with the Federal Trade Commission over predatory lending at one of its divisions.

git log -G SEARCH-STR |while read c t; do case $c in "commit") git grep SEARCH-STR $t ;; esac; done

while read c t
 do

 esac
done

column21:
Split your binary up in parts according to binwalk:
file=firmware.bin;c=0;s=0;for n in $( (binwalk $file | grep "^[0-9]";wc -c $file) | cut -d\  -f1);do c=$(expr $c + 1);l=$(expr $n - $s);echo start=$s end=$n len=$l;dd if=$file of=part${c}-$file bs=1 skip=$s count=$l;s=$n;done

group by $k
let $c:=count($s)
order by $c descending
return <w k="{$k}" c="{$c}"/>)[position()=(1 to 10)]
